  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Leaders for Peace and Gender Justice</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">- A gender assessment is held in CICA member churches
- Theologies, policies and programmes on gender justice of CICA and member churches foster gender justice and protect church communities from injustices and abuses through active monitoring 
- Empower church leaders, communities and families to peacefully resolve conflicts   
- Safe spaces/channels to denounce abuses are established 
- Alliances built nationally and internationally with leaders and faith movements for gender justice through participation in exchanges/events
- Engagement and training of faith and community leaders on rights-based peacebuilding programs using different platforms 
- Establishment of community &#x201C;peace nuclei&#x201D;, implementation of respective peace programmes/initiatives and conflict mapping/resolution
- Monitoring of the peace, governance and social situation is implemented and shared (advocacy)
- Exchange and dialogue with Building Bridges Platform</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Women and girls in communities, groups and organisations are better able to resiliently manage resources and have increased participation, decision making.
- Gender justice is increased in churches and communities
- Girls and women leadership opportunities increase in churches and communities
- Boys and men develop more positive masculinities with more respect towards women and less GBV
- Discrimination and conflicts based on gender decrease in families, churches and communities
- Women/girls and men/boys feel more secure of gender justice/GBV in churches and in communities

Leaders of faith based organisations and community bodies adopt values and principles of reconciliation, justice and peace and become role models for change.
- Power holders at local and national level are influencing and seeking to reduce conflict 
- Church and community-based groups promote dialogue and cooperation and identify ways of addressing and transforming conflicts</narrative>
  </description>
